results.notes:
Fruiting beneath 2nd growth Douglas fir.
Cap: abruptly umbonate/papillate disc coated in radiating fibrils. Disc is dark grayish brown(drying blackish). Youngest specimen with nearly conical appearance.
Stem: bulbous base vertically striate. Younger specimens with shorter sheathed flocking.
Odor: slightly spermatic, faintly aromatic/cedar.
Harvested all 3 specimens.
Slide #1: Spore printing cap directly on a glass slide.
Slide #2: removed a single gill from mature specimen and mounted on a glass slide in KOH to analyze cystidia/gill edge.
Cheilocystidia: Metuloid, large. Some with broader abrupt bases. Apexes encrusted with golden crystals.
Pleurocystidia: abundant, globose.
Spores from gill mount: elliptical to narrowly elliptical with slightly irregular texture(wrinkled). Some spores with faint apiculus like tip, inequilateral in side laying spores. Medium sized.
Slide#1 micro:
Spore Print: grayish brown.
Mounted spore print in KOH.
Spores from mount: elliptical to narrowly elliptic with a few longer nearly cylindrical spores.
Medium sized, smoother in texture than gill mount spores analyzed earlier.
Dehydrated all specimens and bagged for herbarium collection/genetic record.

results.notes:
This A. muscaria colony was found growing at the basin of an aspen tree (mycorrhizal) in the Littlefield Ornamentals Trial Garden on the University of Maine campus. These amanita were found growing on leaf litter covered moist soil. Within this one colony, there were four A. muscaria growing, all of different age ranges from pre-mature to mature. With that being said, measurements in the field varied. In the field, immature A. muscariaâs cap measured ~ 6 cm x 6 cm, while mature caps measured ~ 13 cm x 12 cm. Immature stipes measured ~ 6 cm tall x 1.5 cm thick, while mature stipes measured ~ 9 cm tall x 2.5 cm thick.

Mature A. muscaria presented a sunken cap with a depressed center. They also possessed some splits around the cap margin. Caps were a yellow to bright yellow color with a tan color towards the center. All over the caps were very soft/sticky cottony warts which were very interesting to touch! These are remnants of A. muscariaâs universal veil. A. muscariaâs gills were white in color (tan after harvested and sitting out) and narrow â just barely free from the stipe. It should be noted that there were some unequal shorter gills.

Mature A. Muscariaâs stipe was white to off-white in color and possessed an annulus and small volva! Its annulus represents remnants of its partial veil and volva represent remnants of its universal veil. Stipe was a bit fragile to the touch.
